        <div class="section-label">Environmental Science</div>
        <h2 class="section-heading">PFAS &amp; Ocean<br>Contamination</h2>
        <p>Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) are persistent environmental contaminants found in increasingly remote ocean environments. The PML is building the first rigorous <strong>global baseline dataset</strong> for ocean PFAS concentrations, spanning Arctic polar stations to Caribbean open waters.</p>
        <p>This program operates in active partnership with the <strong>Sustainable Seas Institute</strong> and its research vessel R/V Dawn, providing unique sampling access to locations that are logistically inaccessible to conventional research programs. Field campaigns in 2025 reached the geographic North Pole, the magnetic North Pole, and the Arctic pole of inaccessibility.</p>
        <p>A global synthesis manuscript co-authored with researchers from the University of Rhode Island is in preparation, targeting <strong>Nature Water</strong>. A companion NSF Chemical Oceanography proposal targets an Indian River Lagoon PFAS baseline study.</p>

        <div class="finding-block">
          <div class="finding-label">Sampling Reach</div>
          <p>PML field campaigns have collected samples from the geographic North Pole, the magnetic North Pole, the Arctic pole of inaccessibility, and multiple Caribbean open-ocean stations aboard R/V Dawn, with South Pacific expansion underway.</p>
