<!-- ===== PROGRAM 03: MICROPLASTICS ===== -->
<section style="background: var(--navy-mid); padding: 88px 0;" id="microplastics">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="program-layout">

      <div class="program-text">
        <div class="program-number">03</div>
        <div class="section-label">Fracture Mechanics &amp; Biointerface</div>
        <h2 class="section-heading">Microplastics Fracture<br>&amp; Cytotoxicity</h2>
        <p>Environmental microplastics span enormous variation in particle shape. Existing toxicity models treat shape as a secondary variable, yet the jagged geometry of fractured particles directly governs how they interact with cell membranes. The PML is developing a quantitative framework that makes particle shape a <strong>first-class mechanistic variable</strong> in cytotoxicity prediction.</p>
        <p>Our group has introduced the <strong>Jagged Shape Factor (JSF)</strong> and the <strong>Fracture Vertex Model (FVM)</strong> to characterize and predict shape-driven toxicological behavior. PhD student Md. Shah Nawaz Arafin leads this experimental and computational program, with three manuscripts in preparation.</p>
        <p>An NSF CBET Interfacial Engineering proposal is in development, supported by a full budget, facilities gap analysis, and scientific white paper. The program complements our ocean contamination work by providing mechanistic insight into the downstream biological effects of the particles we detect in field campaigns.</p>

        <div class="finding-block">
          <div class="finding-label">Novel Framework</div>
          <p>The Jagged Shape Factor (JSF) and Fracture Vertex Model (FVM) provide the first quantitative link between microplastic fracture surface geometry and predicted cytotoxicity, enabling shape-informed environmental risk assessment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="tag-row">
          <span class="tag">NSF CBET (Pending)</span>
